10
00:00:31.440 --> 00:00:33.480
So you have a 62-year-old obese male

11
00:00:33.480 --> 00:00:35.850
with diabetes and anemia who presents to your office.

12
00:00:35.850 --> 00:00:37.350
Which of the following anemias

13
00:00:37.350 --> 00:00:40.800
could falsely elevate his A1C?

14
00:00:40.800 --> 00:00:42.690
Hemolytic anemia, sickle cell,

15
00:00:42.690 --> 00:00:45.033
iron deficiency, or acute blood loss?

16
00:00:50.460 --> 00:00:51.870
Very good.

17
00:00:51.870 --> 00:00:54.183
So, iron deficiency anemia.

18
00:00:55.230 --> 00:00:57.960
All right, you need to know the diagnosis of diabetes.

19
00:00:57.960 --> 00:00:58.950
I know it seems silly.

20
00:00:58.950 --> 00:01:03.423
But the A1C of 6.5 fasting glucose of 126.

21
00:01:04.590 --> 00:01:09.590
You can also use a glucose load or a random glucose,

22
00:01:10.230 --> 00:01:12.240
but they have to be symptomatic with that.

23
00:01:12.240 --> 00:01:13.890
And you need two values

24
00:01:13.890 --> 00:01:15.720
and they can be the same value twice.

25
00:01:15.720 --> 00:01:17.553
So you can have two A1Cs.

26
00:01:19.350 --> 00:01:22.650
So notice that things that increase your A1C,

27
00:01:22.650 --> 00:01:27.650
so the glucose gets globbed onto the blood molecule.

28
00:01:27.720 --> 00:01:32.340
So in iron deficiency anemia, you have really small cells,

29
00:01:32.340 --> 00:01:33.960
but a lot of those small cells,

30
00:01:33.960 --> 00:01:36.750
so you're gonna have more glucose stuck on them.

31
00:01:36.750 --> 00:01:40.800
In things like when when you have something

32
00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:42.600
like sickle cell or blood loss,

33
00:01:42.600 --> 00:01:44.490
you're going to actually have fewer blood cells

34
00:01:44.490 --> 00:01:46.860
so that there's less glucose attached,

35
00:01:46.860 --> 00:01:50.130
so your A1C will be falsely low, okay?

36
00:01:50.130 --> 00:01:52.920
They do like to ask those questions.

37
00:01:52.920 --> 00:01:55.560
Please know the difference between type one and type two

38
00:01:55.560 --> 00:01:57.180
and when you start screening.

39
00:01:57.180 --> 00:02:01.170
So in type one, we usually start screening five years after

40
00:02:01.170 --> 00:02:05.280
for things like retinopathy, after the diagnosis,

41
00:02:05.280 --> 00:02:08.310
because it's a fairly acute onset disease

42
00:02:08.310 --> 00:02:10.530
while type two is an insidious onset

43
00:02:10.530 --> 00:02:12.480
that you've been getting for some time.

44
00:02:13.350 --> 00:02:16.740
A couple years ago there was an article in the AAFP

45
00:02:16.740 --> 00:02:19.380
on maturity onset diabetes of the young.

46
00:02:19.380 --> 00:02:23.850
And there's already been a question on the in-training exam,

47
00:02:23.850 --> 00:02:26.220
so please know what MODY is.

48
00:02:26.220 --> 00:02:28.620
The question they're probably gonna answer is,

49
00:02:28.620 --> 00:02:29.460
how do you treat it?

50
00:02:29.460 --> 00:02:32.220
And the sulfonylureas is actually the answer.

51
00:02:32.220 --> 00:02:35.700
because in MODY it's a mild diabetes

52
00:02:35.700 --> 00:02:37.590
and they usually just need a little touch

53
00:02:37.590 --> 00:02:40.593
of sulfonylureas to get them in control.

54
00:02:42.570 --> 00:02:44.640
Self-management.

55
00:02:44.640 --> 00:02:46.410
What you need to know about this

56
00:02:46.410 --> 00:02:49.080
is continuous glucose monitoring

57
00:02:49.080 --> 00:02:50.730
because that's where it's all going.

58
00:02:50.730 --> 00:02:55.730
CGMs are revolutionizing the treatment of diabetes.

59
00:02:59.174 --> 00:03:02.160
But if we're just doing finger sticks,

60
00:03:02.160 --> 00:03:05.070
there are times when you have to monitor your sugars.

61
00:03:05.070 --> 00:03:08.073
So if you're on insulin, if you're changing your therapies,

62
00:03:10.139 --> 00:03:13.260
if you're ill, you know, you need to know what's going on.

63
00:03:13.260 --> 00:03:15.570
But for those people who are well controlled,

64
00:03:15.570 --> 00:03:18.360
they don't need to be doing finger sticks all the time.

65
00:03:18.360 --> 00:03:20.460
That's just, that's really a waste of time.

66
00:03:20.460 --> 00:03:23.880
You can see the benefit actually of self-monitoring

67
00:03:23.880 --> 00:03:26.610
with finger sticks goes away after about a year.

68
00:03:26.610 --> 00:03:28.650
But we're gonna see this different now

69
00:03:28.650 --> 00:03:31.470
with continuous glucose monitors.

70
00:03:31.470 --> 00:03:33.270
Management goals,

71
00:03:33.270 --> 00:03:36.000
probably the best number is still seven.

72
00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:38.670
But with all of these new diabetes drugs,

73
00:03:38.670 --> 00:03:41.130
we're really pushing that below seven

74
00:03:41.130 --> 00:03:44.670
and people should, you know, we're now saying

75
00:03:44.670 --> 00:03:48.630
that if you are above seven, you're not well controlled.

76
00:03:48.630 --> 00:03:50.520
Now remember that there are different values

77
00:03:50.520 --> 00:03:51.353
for different people.

78
00:03:51.353 --> 00:03:52.680
If you're end of life,

79
00:03:52.680 --> 00:03:55.530
what is the value of getting someone to 6.5?

80
00:03:55.530 --> 00:03:58.350
So if you can just get them in reasonable control

81
00:03:58.350 --> 00:04:00.990
and get them under eight, that's good.

82
00:04:00.990 --> 00:04:04.770
And blood pressure control, very, very, very important.

83
00:04:04.770 --> 00:04:07.350
You can see that the number has been 140 over 90,

84
00:04:07.350 --> 00:04:09.480
but most organizations push for it

85
00:04:09.480 --> 00:04:12.783
to be significantly lower, 130 over 80.

86
00:04:14.987 --> 00:04:18.330
If you have kidney disease, the American Kidney Association

87
00:04:18.330 --> 00:04:20.400
likes it less than 125 over 75.

88
00:04:20.400 --> 00:04:23.340
So the values will change for different patients,

89
00:04:23.340 --> 00:04:25.200
and the lower the blood pressure in general,

90
00:04:25.200 --> 00:04:26.313
the better it is.

91
00:04:27.870 --> 00:04:31.050
All right, let's talk about the therapies.

92
00:04:31.050 --> 00:04:35.340
This is the new model that we're using, so don't freak out.

93
00:04:35.340 --> 00:04:38.220
It's really not that hard, okay?

94
00:04:38.220 --> 00:04:39.810
We've made it easy.

95
00:04:39.810 --> 00:04:42.900
I know it looks hard, but this is what is.

96
00:04:42.900 --> 00:04:46.800
When you look up there, number one, metformin.

97
00:04:46.800 --> 00:04:50.370
Then you go to the left, and we're gonna talk about those.

98
00:04:50.370 --> 00:04:54.630
So if on the left, if you have other conditions,

99
00:04:54.630 --> 00:04:59.370
heart disease, heart failure, atherosclerotic heart disease,

100
00:04:59.370 --> 00:05:02.580
or kidney disease, we're gonna treat that differently.

101
00:05:02.580 --> 00:05:07.500
Otherwise after metformin, then we're just gonna make sure

102
00:05:07.500 --> 00:05:10.293
that we don't make people hypoglycemic.

103
00:05:11.370 --> 00:05:13.980
We're gonna talk about getting them to lose weight.

104
00:05:13.980 --> 00:05:17.130
And then we're gonna have that category on the right

105
00:05:17.130 --> 00:05:19.620
for people who can't afford anything else.

106
00:05:19.620 --> 00:05:20.913
All right, here we go.

107
00:05:22.050 --> 00:05:24.540
Which of the following medications affects B12 levels

108
00:05:24.540 --> 00:05:26.073
necessitating monitoring?

109
00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:31.273
Metformin, acarbose, glyburide, repaglinide, or sitagliptin.

110
00:05:35.670 --> 00:05:37.590
Perfect. You guys all knew this

111
00:05:37.590 --> 00:05:41.760
And new study out that we probably ought to be

112
00:05:41.760 --> 00:05:45.720
looking at B12 on a yearly basis,

113
00:05:45.720 --> 00:05:49.203
just getting a B12 level on anybody who's on Metformin.

114
00:05:50.130 --> 00:05:51.990
All right, metformin's is your number one choice.

115
00:05:51.990 --> 00:05:54.150
It's still the number one choice.

116
00:05:54.150 --> 00:05:56.850
It decreases gluconeogenesis in the liver.

117
00:05:56.850 --> 00:06:00.450
It's also a peripheral insulin sensitizer,

118
00:06:00.450 --> 00:06:03.420
so that's why it works so well in type two diabetes.

119
00:06:03.420 --> 00:06:05.910
It improves cardiovascular outcomes,

120
00:06:05.910 --> 00:06:09.690
it decreases mortality, it has the best data,

121
00:06:09.690 --> 00:06:12.480
so it's very important that we continue to use it.

122
00:06:12.480 --> 00:06:16.470
It's the only oral medication for children

123
00:06:16.470 --> 00:06:19.403
that's FDA approved in children, okay?

124
00:06:20.697 --> 00:06:23.130
You can still use it in pregnancy.

125
00:06:23.130 --> 00:06:28.130
We are stopping it now when the GFR is less than 30,

126
00:06:28.650 --> 00:06:31.680
it's not based on creatinine, it's GFR.

127
00:06:31.680 --> 00:06:34.620
Don't start it if the GFR is less than 45.

128
00:06:34.620 --> 00:06:36.870
We're still stopping it for IV contrast.

129
00:06:36.870 --> 00:06:39.663
And again, check for BB 12 levels.

130
00:06:42.900 --> 00:06:45.840
53-year-old male with well-controlled type two diabetes

131
00:06:45.840 --> 00:06:48.480
on metformin 1,000 milligrams BID.

132
00:06:48.480 --> 00:06:50.520
He was hospitalized last month for chest pain

133
00:06:50.520 --> 00:06:53.040
and had a right coronary artery angioplasty.

134
00:06:53.040 --> 00:06:54.810
Which medication should you add?

135
00:06:54.810 --> 00:06:57.763
Semaglutide, pioglitazone, sitagliptin, or nateglinide.

136
00:06:58.650 --> 00:07:02.760
So we're gonna go back and work through that big chart

137
00:07:02.760 --> 00:07:04.510
that I showed you in the beginning.

138
00:07:10.380 --> 00:07:11.493
Yes, semaglutide.

139
00:07:12.330 --> 00:07:13.623
And this is why.

140
00:07:14.580 --> 00:07:19.580
If you have atherosclerotic coronary vascular disease,

141
00:07:19.590 --> 00:07:23.550
if you have heart failure, if you have kidney disease,

142
00:07:23.550 --> 00:07:27.270
you should be on, even if you're well-controlled,

143
00:07:27.270 --> 00:07:31.770
if you're on metformin and your A1C is 6.5,

144
00:07:31.770 --> 00:07:36.770
you should still be on an SGLT2 for most of those things.

145
00:07:38.190 --> 00:07:41.730
If it's just atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease,

146
00:07:41.730 --> 00:07:44.010
either a GLP-1 or an SGLT2.

147
00:07:44.010 --> 00:07:46.050
Doesn't matter, pick whichever one.

148
00:07:46.050 --> 00:07:48.983
If they're overweight, I would pick the GLP-1.

149
00:07:52.170 --> 00:07:55.440
But either one, I've given you the ones there

150
00:07:55.440 --> 00:07:58.770
that are recommended in those categories.

151
00:07:58.770 --> 00:08:02.010
If you have heart failure or chronic kidney disease,

152
00:08:02.010 --> 00:08:05.310
expect they're going to ask this question of you.

153
00:08:05.310 --> 00:08:07.203
You need an SGLT2.

154
00:08:09.120 --> 00:08:10.770
Pick the SGLT2.

155
00:08:10.770 --> 00:08:13.050
The nice thing about this is no matter what,

156
00:08:13.050 --> 00:08:15.023
you can pick an SGLT2, okay?

157
00:08:16.320 --> 00:08:18.060
But if it's heart failure or kidney disease,

158
00:08:18.060 --> 00:08:22.290
SGLT2 is your first choice, GLP-1 is your second

159
00:08:22.290 --> 00:08:25.383
if for some reason they can't take the the SGLT2.

160
00:08:26.430 --> 00:08:29.610
And that's even if they're controlled, okay?

161
00:08:29.610 --> 00:08:32.490
So we're gonna move to those very quickly

162
00:08:32.490 --> 00:08:34.500
in anybody who has those diseases.

163
00:08:34.500 --> 00:08:36.360
Let's look at the SGLT2s.

164
00:08:36.360 --> 00:08:38.340
These are the currently available.

165
00:08:38.340 --> 00:08:40.923
Notice there's a new one down there, bexagliflozin.

166
00:08:41.910 --> 00:08:44.280
And notice that they all have different GFRs

167
00:08:44.280 --> 00:08:46.620
that you can use 'em down to

168
00:08:46.620 --> 00:08:48.930
and we're using them lower and lower.

169
00:08:48.930 --> 00:08:52.740
You'll notice that it says recommended in nephropathy

170
00:08:52.740 --> 00:08:55.050
if the SGLT2 is over 30.

171
00:08:55.050 --> 00:08:57.210
Remember how these drugs work?

172
00:08:57.210 --> 00:09:01.410
They reabsorb, they block the reabsorption

173
00:09:01.410 --> 00:09:03.390
of glucose in the kidney.

174
00:09:03.390 --> 00:09:06.120
So glucose comes out, water comes out,

175
00:09:06.120 --> 00:09:09.210
we reabsorb glucose in water,

176
00:09:09.210 --> 00:09:11.520
but they're blocking glucose, so you're just literally

177
00:09:11.520 --> 00:09:14.280
going to pee out the sugar in your blood.

178
00:09:14.280 --> 00:09:15.870
That's how they work.

179
00:09:15.870 --> 00:09:19.380
And so if your kidneys aren't working,

180
00:09:19.380 --> 00:09:22.170
you can't expect them to do what you,

181
00:09:22.170 --> 00:09:23.580
so it's not going to work.

182
00:09:23.580 --> 00:09:27.510
The drug just simply won't work if your GFR is too low.

183
00:09:27.510 --> 00:09:28.770
Look at all the side effects.

184
00:09:28.770 --> 00:09:31.830
They slow progression of kidney disease.

185
00:09:31.830 --> 00:09:35.790
They decrease risk of MI, stroke, cardiovascular disease.

186
00:09:35.790 --> 00:09:37.743
These are important drugs.

187
00:09:39.210 --> 00:09:42.390
The question they ask is almost always about DKA.

188
00:09:42.390 --> 00:09:44.730
You can increase your risk of DKA,

189
00:09:44.730 --> 00:09:49.200
even at a type two diabetic if they're using an SGLT2,

190
00:09:49.200 --> 00:09:51.300
and there is a slight increase risk

191
00:09:51.300 --> 00:09:56.300
of foot ulcers becoming even worse

192
00:09:56.550 --> 00:09:58.650
and ending up with a foot amputation.

193
00:09:58.650 --> 00:10:02.493
That's a very small risk, but you should be aware of it.

194
00:10:03.990 --> 00:10:08.070
The GLP-1s, these are subcutaneous injections.

195
00:10:08.070 --> 00:10:09.840
I talked about 'em before.

196
00:10:09.840 --> 00:10:14.840
They slow gastric emptying and increase satiety.

197
00:10:15.210 --> 00:10:17.580
Liraglutide was,

198
00:10:17.580 --> 00:10:19.890
really exenatide was the first in this category,

199
00:10:19.890 --> 00:10:23.283
but liraglutide then came out, it's a daily one.

200
00:10:24.660 --> 00:10:29.660
And notice L, liraglutide, is not secreted renally,

201
00:10:30.480 --> 00:10:32.970
so you can continue to use it

202
00:10:32.970 --> 00:10:34.953
even in significant renal failure.

203
00:10:36.789 --> 00:10:39.510
And semaglutide, of course, we've talked about before.

204
00:10:39.510 --> 00:10:42.450
And then tirzepatide is the newest in this category,

205
00:10:42.450 --> 00:10:44.700
which is also a GIP.

206
00:10:44.700 --> 00:10:48.660
They will ask you about pancreatitis risk with this

207
00:10:48.660 --> 00:10:52.263
and they will ask about thyroid cell tumors.

208
00:10:53.462 --> 00:10:57.600
So if you have anyone who's had a thyroid tumor,

209
00:10:57.600 --> 00:10:59.733
they are not a candidate for these drugs.

210
00:11:00.960 --> 00:11:05.790
All right, so your first step is metformin,

211
00:11:05.790 --> 00:11:08.280
and then if they have any kind of,

212
00:11:08.280 --> 00:11:12.390
if they have heart failure, cardiovascular disease,

213
00:11:12.390 --> 00:11:14.723
or kidney failure, you're going to add

214
00:11:14.723 --> 00:11:17.790
a GLP-1 or an SGLT2, right?

215
00:11:17.790 --> 00:11:22.680
Okay, after metformin, if you just need another drug,

216
00:11:22.680 --> 00:11:25.590
they don't have any of these things, so they're not on that.

217
00:11:25.590 --> 00:11:29.700
Then you could also add a DPP-4 inhibitor

218
00:11:29.700 --> 00:11:31.563
or thiazolidinedione.

219
00:11:33.960 --> 00:11:36.870
You can also add, notice every single category

220
00:11:36.870 --> 00:11:39.300
you can also add your SGLT2 or GLP-1.

221
00:11:39.300 --> 00:11:42.603
If you want weight loss, you're gonna add GLP-1 or SGLT2.

222
00:11:43.620 --> 00:11:46.170
But if cost is your major issue

223
00:11:46.170 --> 00:11:48.750
and you need something beyond metformin,

224
00:11:48.750 --> 00:11:49.583
oh, sorry,

225
00:11:51.224 --> 00:11:53.610
then you're gonna go to a thiazolidinedione

226
00:11:53.610 --> 00:11:55.023
or a sulfonylurea.

227
00:11:56.010 --> 00:12:00.857
Those are the only two places if cost is your reason.

228
00:12:01.980 --> 00:12:05.910
Okay, let's look really quickly at the DPP-4s.

229
00:12:05.910 --> 00:12:10.710
So what DPP-4 does is it inhibits the re-uptake of GLP-1.

230
00:12:10.710 --> 00:12:14.580
GLP-1 is excreted when you eat,

231
00:12:14.580 --> 00:12:17.070
but it comes out very quickly

232
00:12:17.070 --> 00:12:19.740
and it lasts for a very short period of time,

233
00:12:19.740 --> 00:12:22.170
but it does increase your satiety.

234
00:12:22.170 --> 00:12:27.170
And so it's a, you know, it's a very important hormone.

235
00:12:28.950 --> 00:12:31.860
And so DPP-4 blocks the reabsorption

236
00:12:31.860 --> 00:12:35.310
so your normal GLP-1 stays around longer.

237
00:12:35.310 --> 00:12:38.640
And it's given as an oral medication once a day,

238
00:12:38.640 --> 00:12:40.890
but it's going to work primarily with meals

239
00:12:40.890 --> 00:12:42.630
because of the way it works.

240
00:12:42.630 --> 00:12:45.240
Linagliptin, and the other L here,

241
00:12:45.240 --> 00:12:48.270
linagliptin is not renally excreted.

242
00:12:48.270 --> 00:12:49.350
The others are,

243
00:12:49.350 --> 00:12:52.203
so you have to be careful of those in renal failure.

244
00:12:53.340 --> 00:12:54.720
The biggest thing with these drugs

245
00:12:54.720 --> 00:12:57.660
is they just aren't a lot of bang for your buck.

246
00:12:57.660 --> 00:13:00.417
They work well, they don't have very many side effects,

247
00:13:00.417 --> 00:13:02.580
but they just don't work as well

248
00:13:02.580 --> 00:13:04.983
as the GLP-1s or the SGLT2s.

249
00:13:06.300 --> 00:13:09.600
Thiazolidinediones, don't throw them away entirely.

250
00:13:09.600 --> 00:13:11.610
Pioglitazone works,

251
00:13:11.610 --> 00:13:14.490
it's a little bit like metformin works at the liver

252
00:13:14.490 --> 00:13:16.590
and then a little bit peripherally.

253
00:13:16.590 --> 00:13:20.670
Thiazolidinediones work peripherally.

254
00:13:20.670 --> 00:13:22.410
They're insulin sensitizers

255
00:13:22.410 --> 00:13:25.410
and also work a little bit at the liver, okay?

256
00:13:25.410 --> 00:13:27.873
And they can be used with metformin.

257
00:13:30.570 --> 00:13:32.220
The biggest bad thing about these

258
00:13:34.870 --> 00:13:37.050
is the propensity of patients

259
00:13:37.050 --> 00:13:39.690
to take on fluid when they take them.

260
00:13:39.690 --> 00:13:42.360
And so you can't use them, there's a black box warning

261
00:13:42.360 --> 00:13:44.940
for class III or IV heart failure.

262
00:13:44.940 --> 00:13:47.240
And that's the question that they like to ask.

263
00:13:48.900 --> 00:13:51.840
55-year-old with newly diagnosed diabetes and hypertension

264
00:13:51.840 --> 00:13:54.630
with chronic renal failure and creatinine of 2.4.

265
00:13:54.630 --> 00:13:56.460
Which medication would be the safest

266
00:13:56.460 --> 00:13:58.440
with regard to renal function?

267
00:13:58.440 --> 00:14:02.337
Acarbose, glyburide, sitagliptin, or glipizide?

268
00:14:07.290 --> 00:14:09.600
Ooh, this is a hard question.

269
00:14:09.600 --> 00:14:12.363
And the answer is glipizide.

270
00:14:13.440 --> 00:14:17.795
So, we're gonna go through all of these so you'll get it.

271
00:14:17.795 --> 00:14:19.560
Sulfonylureas.

272
00:14:19.560 --> 00:14:22.023
You can use sulfonylureas in most people,

273
00:14:22.968 --> 00:14:24.750
but glyburide has a metabolite

274
00:14:24.750 --> 00:14:27.204
that's secreted through the kidney,

275
00:14:27.204 --> 00:14:28.980
so you have to be careful of using it

276
00:14:28.980 --> 00:14:31.110
in patients who have renal failure.

277
00:14:31.110 --> 00:14:33.933
Glipizide and glimeperide are okay.

278
00:14:35.250 --> 00:14:37.380
The nice thing about the sulfonylureas again,

279
00:14:37.380 --> 00:14:40.260
is that you can use them in just about everybody.

280
00:14:40.260 --> 00:14:42.360
In older patients, be very careful

281
00:14:42.360 --> 00:14:44.160
and use them only at low doses,

282
00:14:44.160 --> 00:14:47.070
but you can use them in mild renal insufficiency,

283
00:14:47.070 --> 00:14:50.940
in cardiac problems, in patients with hepatic failure,

284
00:14:50.940 --> 00:14:52.173
all kinds of things.

285
00:14:53.400 --> 00:14:55.710
But they are just insulin secretagogues.

286
00:14:55.710 --> 00:14:57.750
They just make you secrete more insulin.

287
00:14:57.750 --> 00:15:00.720
And so if a patient's already using insulin,

288
00:15:00.720 --> 00:15:03.120
it's kind of a waste of time.

289
00:15:03.120 --> 00:15:06.795
But for patients that just need a little bit of something,

290
00:15:06.795 --> 00:15:08.490
sulfonylureas can be very helpful

291
00:15:08.490 --> 00:15:11.880
and should stay in your armamentarium because they're cheap.

292
00:15:11.880 --> 00:15:15.360
The meglitinides are just,

293
00:15:15.360 --> 00:15:17.670
they work like rapid-acting sulfonylureas,

294
00:15:17.670 --> 00:15:21.030
so they just cause insulin secretion

295
00:15:21.030 --> 00:15:23.070
for a short period of time when you take them.

296
00:15:23.070 --> 00:15:24.660
So they're taken at meals.

297
00:15:24.660 --> 00:15:27.420
So if you have like an elderly patient

298
00:15:27.420 --> 00:15:30.330
who takes their sulfonylurea and then doesn't eat,

299
00:15:30.330 --> 00:15:33.360
switching them to a meglitinide would be a good choice.

300
00:15:33.360 --> 00:15:36.153
Otherwise, they really don't have much use anymore.

301
00:15:37.738 --> 00:15:40.860
Alpha-glucosidase inhibitors, acarbose and miglitol,

302
00:15:40.860 --> 00:15:43.230
block the breakdown of carbohydrates,

303
00:15:43.230 --> 00:15:45.780
of disaccharides in the gut.

304
00:15:45.780 --> 00:15:48.330
So they looked like they'd be really good,

305
00:15:48.330 --> 00:15:50.700
you just can't absorb the glucose.

306
00:15:50.700 --> 00:15:53.070
It's just gonna pass on through the gut.

307
00:15:53.070 --> 00:15:54.900
So you get a lot of GI problems,

308
00:15:54.900 --> 00:15:56.700
as you can imagine, with these drugs.

309
00:15:56.700 --> 00:15:59.580
And again, just not a lot of bang for your buck.

310
00:15:59.580 --> 00:16:01.350
And they also can't be used

311
00:16:01.350 --> 00:16:03.570
with a creatinine greater than two.

312
00:16:03.570 --> 00:16:06.780
And so that's why that choice was there.

313
00:16:06.780 --> 00:16:09.120
And remember, sitagliptin was on that list.

314
00:16:09.120 --> 00:16:12.120
And remember, linagliptin is the only one that we can use

315
00:16:12.120 --> 00:16:14.880
in renal failure of the DPP-4s.

316
00:16:14.880 --> 00:16:18.273
So that's why the answer to the the question was glipizide.

317
00:16:19.620 --> 00:16:22.590
All right, so now after we've done metformin

318
00:16:22.590 --> 00:16:24.960
and we've added another drug and we're still not controlled,

319
00:16:24.960 --> 00:16:27.810
we simply add another drug, okay?

320
00:16:27.810 --> 00:16:29.223
Anything from the list.

321
00:16:30.570 --> 00:16:32.310
But just be careful that you're not using

322
00:16:32.310 --> 00:16:34.230
two drugs that are similar,

323
00:16:34.230 --> 00:16:38.880
like using a DPP-4 and a GLP-1 make no sense,

324
00:16:38.880 --> 00:16:41.460
because they're doing essentially the same thing.

325
00:16:41.460 --> 00:16:44.310
So make sure you're using drugs with different mechanisms.

326
00:16:44.310 --> 00:16:47.910
Metformin can be used with nearly everything.

327
00:16:47.910 --> 00:16:51.720
And as you will see, clear at the back of my slides

328
00:16:51.720 --> 00:16:54.780
I gave you a list of the combination drugs,

329
00:16:54.780 --> 00:16:56.673
which is like a page long,

330
00:16:57.750 --> 00:17:01.800
and really almost every drug is combined with metformin,

331
00:17:01.800 --> 00:17:03.180
all the oral drugs.

332
00:17:03.180 --> 00:17:06.420
So we don't use the combos too often

333
00:17:06.420 --> 00:17:10.233
because they just are a little bit clunkier to use.

334
00:17:12.555 --> 00:17:14.010
And when they're combined with metformin,

335
00:17:14.010 --> 00:17:15.840
they don't really save you all that much

336
00:17:15.840 --> 00:17:17.193
because metformin's cheap.

337
00:17:18.210 --> 00:17:19.770
You guys should all know insulin.

338
00:17:19.770 --> 00:17:22.200
They tend to not ask very many questions about it.

339
00:17:22.200 --> 00:17:25.350
Bioavailability is faster in the abdomen.

340
00:17:25.350 --> 00:17:27.270
If you put it in the thigh you have to be careful

341
00:17:27.270 --> 00:17:29.970
with exercising after that.

342
00:17:29.970 --> 00:17:34.890
We're seeing a lot of changes in hospital use of insulin now

343
00:17:34.890 --> 00:17:39.090
in using more corrective factor insulin.

344
00:17:39.090 --> 00:17:42.060
And a lot of these changes are because of the new,

345
00:17:42.060 --> 00:17:44.583
because of things like the GLP-1s.

346
00:17:45.780 --> 00:17:47.460
Intensive insulin therapy.

347
00:17:47.460 --> 00:17:48.960
The only thing I wanna say about this

348
00:17:48.960 --> 00:17:51.690
is when you have someone who is newly diagnosed

349
00:17:51.690 --> 00:17:53.100
who's totally out of control,

350
00:17:53.100 --> 00:17:56.580
do not be afraid to use insulin early on

351
00:17:56.580 --> 00:17:59.100
to get that patient under control.

352
00:17:59.100 --> 00:18:00.870
And you can always take them off again.

353
00:18:00.870 --> 00:18:03.600
We had some, you know, some idea at some point

354
00:18:03.600 --> 00:18:08.340
that if we didn't, you know, once people got on insulin,

355
00:18:08.340 --> 00:18:10.770
they could never get off, which is totally crazy.

356
00:18:10.770 --> 00:18:13.983
And so don't be afraid to use it to get them under control.

357
00:18:15.240 --> 00:18:17.370
These are your long-acting insulins.

358
00:18:17.370 --> 00:18:20.400
NPH is kind of a medium dose.

359
00:18:20.400 --> 00:18:23.929
Glargine has been the standard for a long, long time.

360
00:18:23.929 --> 00:18:27.240
Detemir or Levemir is coming off the market next month.

361
00:18:27.240 --> 00:18:28.500
So if you've got anybody on it,

362
00:18:28.500 --> 00:18:29.820
you're gonna have to switch them

363
00:18:29.820 --> 00:18:32.910
either to glargine or to degludec.

364
00:18:32.910 --> 00:18:35.220
It's coming, literally it's coming off the market

365
00:18:35.220 --> 00:18:36.920
to make more room to make Ozempic.

366
00:18:38.820 --> 00:18:41.403
So, there you go.

367
00:18:42.540 --> 00:18:45.780
And do know that degludec is the longest acting

368
00:18:45.780 --> 00:18:48.450
and has the least hypoglycemia.

369
00:18:48.450 --> 00:18:51.570
So that's the question they like to ask.

370
00:18:51.570 --> 00:18:56.400
The rapid-acting analogs, lispro, aspart, glulisine,

371
00:18:56.400 --> 00:18:57.960
all very similar.

372
00:18:57.960 --> 00:19:01.800
have a short onset of action in about 15 minutes.

373
00:19:01.800 --> 00:19:04.320
You take 'em, you can eat,

374
00:19:04.320 --> 00:19:07.770
you can also take them immediately after you eat.

375
00:19:07.770 --> 00:19:11.310
And they are the basis for what we use in the pumps.

376
00:19:11.310 --> 00:19:14.850
You know, we, so we use these a lot.

377
00:19:14.850 --> 00:19:18.630
Please note that there are new ultra rapid insulins.

378
00:19:18.630 --> 00:19:23.430
They combine them with, lispro and aspart with B vitamins

379
00:19:23.430 --> 00:19:25.560
so that they're absorbed really quickly.

380
00:19:25.560 --> 00:19:29.430
And if you use those, they're gonna be way more expensive,

381
00:19:29.430 --> 00:19:31.170
you're not gonna get much,

382
00:19:31.170 --> 00:19:33.810
they're just gonna act really rapidly.

383
00:19:33.810 --> 00:19:35.040
But the thing about those

384
00:19:35.040 --> 00:19:37.590
is that you have to eat immediately.

385
00:19:37.590 --> 00:19:40.380
So you can not take them 15 minutes before you eat

386
00:19:40.380 --> 00:19:41.220
and then think you're gonna eat.

387
00:19:41.220 --> 00:19:42.720
That's not gonna work.

388
00:19:42.720 --> 00:19:47.463
You need to take them when you're actually ready to eat.

389
00:19:48.330 --> 00:19:50.520
Please note that there is also an inhaled insulin

390
00:19:50.520 --> 00:19:53.430
out on the market, it's Afrezza.

391
00:19:53.430 --> 00:19:56.583
You can't use it if you have any kind of respiratory issues.

392
00:20:00.120 --> 00:20:03.780
The boards continue to stay away from insulin pumps.

393
00:20:03.780 --> 00:20:08.780
I don't know why, but they have become really the mainstay

394
00:20:08.880 --> 00:20:11.940
for patients with difficult to control diabetes

395
00:20:11.940 --> 00:20:16.860
and are really particularly for type one diabetes,

396
00:20:16.860 --> 00:20:19.473
but are used extensively in type two as well,

397
00:20:20.730 --> 00:20:22.950
and are really incredibly good,

398
00:20:22.950 --> 00:20:25.680
particularly with the continuous glucose monitors.

399
00:20:25.680 --> 00:20:27.870
And we're going to see those all.

400
00:20:27.870 --> 00:20:32.100
We're gonna see a system that just does itself.

401
00:20:32.100 --> 00:20:35.040
You know, we're not even gonna have to intervene

402
00:20:35.040 --> 00:20:36.543
because it's gonna do its own.

403
00:20:37.590 --> 00:20:39.720
All right, which of the following medications

404
00:20:39.720 --> 00:20:41.550
would be outside the recommendations

405
00:20:41.550 --> 00:20:43.530
for a 15-year-old with type two diabetes,

406
00:20:43.530 --> 00:20:45.480
hypertension, and hyperlipidemia?

407
00:20:45.480 --> 00:20:48.630
Metformin, sitagliptin, liraglutide,

408
00:20:48.630 --> 00:20:50.613
lisinopril, or pravastatin?

409
00:20:56.850 --> 00:20:59.070
Very good, thank you, you guys are.

410
00:20:59.070 --> 00:21:01.860
So the only oral diabetes medication

411
00:21:01.860 --> 00:21:03.933
is metformin for kids, right?

412
00:21:05.100 --> 00:21:09.810
So in kids we have metformin, and of course insulin,

413
00:21:09.810 --> 00:21:14.373
and also liraglutide is recommended for children now.

414
00:21:15.300 --> 00:21:20.300
And so, but it's a injection, not an oral medication.

415
00:21:22.740 --> 00:21:25.290
I've given you a couple of things there

416
00:21:25.290 --> 00:21:28.713
on metformin and lifestyle change.

417
00:21:30.240 --> 00:21:33.000
In screening for complications in kids,

418
00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:36.780
which are a little bit different than in adults.

419
00:21:36.780 --> 00:21:39.720
And when you start, like retinopathy start at age 15

420
00:21:39.720 --> 00:21:42.690
or five years after the diagnosis, so.

421
00:21:42.690 --> 00:21:44.310
Also, we wanna make sure we're screening

422
00:21:44.310 --> 00:21:47.820
for hypertension and for hypothyroidism.

423
00:21:47.820 --> 00:21:50.340
In kids, if you have type one,

424
00:21:50.340 --> 00:21:53.040
remember it is an autoimmune type disease,

425
00:21:53.040 --> 00:21:58.040
so you wanna screen for hypothyroidism and celiac disease.

426
00:21:58.680 --> 00:22:01.500
So very important to remember those two things.

427
00:22:01.500 --> 00:22:02.670
Hypertension in kids,

428
00:22:02.670 --> 00:22:06.213
we're still treating that with lisinopril.

429
00:22:07.320 --> 00:22:10.770
But remember that if you have a female,

430
00:22:10.770 --> 00:22:13.980
you can't use the ACE inhibitors in someone who's pregnant.

431
00:22:13.980 --> 00:22:18.030
So all of these kids should also be on birth control

432
00:22:18.030 --> 00:22:19.710
if you're using lisinopril.

433
00:22:19.710 --> 00:22:22.620
Preferably a long acting, reversible,

434
00:22:22.620 --> 00:22:24.663
not oral contraceptives.

435
00:22:27.060 --> 00:22:28.140
These are the immunizations.

436
00:22:28.140 --> 00:22:30.360
So just make sure you're getting your influenza yearly.

437
00:22:30.360 --> 00:22:34.110
Now your Covid, PCV20 is now recommended

438
00:22:34.110 --> 00:22:36.660
in all patients with diabetes.

439
00:22:36.660 --> 00:22:40.170
And hepatitis B is recommended in all patients less than 60

440
00:22:40.170 --> 00:22:43.323
and anyone over 60 that you think it would be of benefit to.

441
00:22:45.090 --> 00:22:48.240
These are the complications that we're gonna talk about

442
00:22:48.240 --> 00:22:50.610
really pretty quickly here.

443
00:22:50.610 --> 00:22:52.740
So, screening for complications.

444
00:22:52.740 --> 00:22:54.570
Make sure you're looking for tobacco use,

445
00:22:54.570 --> 00:22:56.070
autonomic neuropathies.

446
00:22:56.070 --> 00:22:58.650
Ask about things like sexual dysfunction.

447
00:22:58.650 --> 00:23:00.450
Hypothyroidism.

448
00:23:00.450 --> 00:23:03.210
Every visit, check their blood pressure

449
00:23:03.210 --> 00:23:06.183
and a visual inspection of their feet.

450
00:23:07.140 --> 00:23:09.420
You don't have to do a monofilament exam,

451
00:23:09.420 --> 00:23:10.440
just look at their feet,

452
00:23:10.440 --> 00:23:12.930
make sure they don't have ulcers on 'em.

453
00:23:12.930 --> 00:23:15.390
The best way to prevent foot ulcers

454
00:23:15.390 --> 00:23:17.640
is have the patients look at their feet.

455
00:23:17.640 --> 00:23:18.660
Look at them every day.

456
00:23:18.660 --> 00:23:20.910
It's the easiest thing you do in diabetes.

457
00:23:20.910 --> 00:23:22.500
Look at your feet.

458
00:23:22.500 --> 00:23:25.923
Again, in type one screen for hypothyroidism and celiac.

459
00:23:27.480 --> 00:23:30.750
Yearly you need to do a monofilament exam,

460
00:23:30.750 --> 00:23:34.980
pulses and vibrations or light touch.

461
00:23:34.980 --> 00:23:38.823
So all of those, it's not just a monofilament exam.

462
00:23:39.720 --> 00:23:43.140
We need a urine microalbumin and creatinine ratio

463
00:23:43.140 --> 00:23:44.340
for nephropathy.

464
00:23:44.340 --> 00:23:47.340
This is not required if you're on an ACE and ARB,

465
00:23:47.340 --> 00:23:50.010
but we're seeing it become back into vogue

466
00:23:50.010 --> 00:23:53.760
because you can moderate how much, you know,

467
00:23:53.760 --> 00:23:56.550
you can increase your dose of their ACE or ARB

468
00:23:56.550 --> 00:23:59.520
and help decrease the amount of microalbumin

469
00:23:59.520 --> 00:24:00.363
in their spleen.

470
00:24:01.290 --> 00:24:04.440
And also screen yearly for depression.

471
00:24:04.440 --> 00:24:06.480
Lipids you should screen for

472
00:24:06.480 --> 00:24:09.450
and a dilated eye exam for retinopathy.

473
00:24:09.450 --> 00:24:10.890
But this has changed.

474
00:24:10.890 --> 00:24:13.260
If you have normal exams,

475
00:24:13.260 --> 00:24:16.373
you only need to get them every two years now, okay?

476
00:24:19.230 --> 00:24:21.210
Prevention of complications are easy,

477
00:24:21.210 --> 00:24:22.950
glycemic control, blood pressure control,

478
00:24:22.950 --> 00:24:25.770
smoking cessation, and correction of dyslipidemia.

479
00:24:25.770 --> 00:24:27.813
It's the standard for everything.

480
00:24:28.830 --> 00:24:31.110
Again, notice that blood pressure control.

481
00:24:31.110 --> 00:24:34.050
Lower if you're younger, lower to prevent stroke.

482
00:24:34.050 --> 00:24:35.733
Lower, lower, lower if we can.

483
00:24:38.762 --> 00:24:42.030
You have a patient on IV fluids and insulin,

484
00:24:42.030 --> 00:24:45.543
that's the initial treatment for ketoacidosis.

485
00:24:46.470 --> 00:24:49.410
For which reason would you delay the use of insulin

486
00:24:49.410 --> 00:24:52.650
in a patient with ketoacidosis?

487
00:24:52.650 --> 00:24:55.091
If their serum glucose is only 260,

488
00:24:55.091 --> 00:24:59.070
if their anion is 11, if their serum potassium is 3.2,

489
00:24:59.070 --> 00:25:01.443
or if the patient is awake and alert.

490
00:25:07.410 --> 00:25:08.610
Very good.

491
00:25:08.610 --> 00:25:13.610
It's the only reason you do not start insulin drip initially

492
00:25:14.220 --> 00:25:16.170
is if their potassium is low.

493
00:25:16.170 --> 00:25:18.750
Usually what you're gonna see in ketoacidosis

494
00:25:18.750 --> 00:25:21.003
is a really high potassium, right?

495
00:25:22.980 --> 00:25:27.570
Because the potassium has all bled out of the cells.

496
00:25:27.570 --> 00:25:31.920
So if it's low, there's no more potassium anywhere.

497
00:25:31.920 --> 00:25:33.840
So you've gotta put potassium in

498
00:25:33.840 --> 00:25:35.580
before you can start your insulin,

499
00:25:35.580 --> 00:25:39.300
otherwise the the treatment

500
00:25:39.300 --> 00:25:42.840
is lots of IV fluids and IV insulin.

501
00:25:42.840 --> 00:25:46.740
Remember that ketoacidosis is just insufficient insulin,

502
00:25:46.740 --> 00:25:48.750
so you get increased gluconeogenesis

503
00:25:48.750 --> 00:25:50.160
and fatty acid oxidation,

504
00:25:50.160 --> 00:25:52.263
which gives you the metabolic acidosis.

505
00:25:53.670 --> 00:25:55.950
And again, it's uncommon in type two,

506
00:25:55.950 --> 00:25:58.320
but more common if they're on an SGLT2,

507
00:25:58.320 --> 00:26:01.020
so we're gonna see a little bit more of it now.

508
00:26:01.020 --> 00:26:02.913
I've given you the criteria there.

509
00:26:03.990 --> 00:26:06.570
Again, volume replacement, insulin drip,

510
00:26:06.570 --> 00:26:08.400
continue the insulin drip.

511
00:26:08.400 --> 00:26:10.140
This is a common question.

512
00:26:10.140 --> 00:26:13.620
Continue the insulin drip until the ketones are gone,

513
00:26:13.620 --> 00:26:16.560
until the acidosis is resolved.

514
00:26:16.560 --> 00:26:18.900
And so what's gonna happen is you're gonna,

515
00:26:18.900 --> 00:26:20.370
when the sugars start to drop,

516
00:26:20.370 --> 00:26:22.920
they get down to around between 200, 250,

517
00:26:22.920 --> 00:26:27.920
you need to add glucose to the IV solution.

518
00:26:28.140 --> 00:26:29.790
But you continue the insulin.

519
00:26:29.790 --> 00:26:32.133
Do not stop the insulin.

520
00:26:33.120 --> 00:26:36.120
And when the potassium gets down around five,

521
00:26:36.120 --> 00:26:40.020
then you need to put potassium into the solution as well.

522
00:26:40.020 --> 00:26:42.300
And if it's already low to start with,

523
00:26:42.300 --> 00:26:45.033
start with potassium in the solution.

524
00:26:45.033 --> 00:26:46.860
Hyperosmolar, hyperglycemic state

525
00:26:46.860 --> 00:26:49.383
is actually fairly uncommon.

526
00:26:50.610 --> 00:26:54.570
It acts very much like diabetic ketoacidosis

527
00:26:54.570 --> 00:26:57.180
and we treat it very much the same,

528
00:26:57.180 --> 00:27:00.693
we're just not in such a big hurry as we are with DKA.

529
00:27:01.740 --> 00:27:06.740
And these patients will be often very confused.

530
00:27:07.500 --> 00:27:10.630
You'll see glucose levels really high, like over 1,000

531
00:27:12.780 --> 00:27:14.730
and so the confusion in all of that

532
00:27:14.730 --> 00:27:17.910
will resolve with the hyperglycemia.

533
00:27:19.620 --> 00:27:22.470
Macrovascular complications for cardiac disease.

534
00:27:22.470 --> 00:27:25.560
The screening for that is a stress echo or stress thallium.

535
00:27:25.560 --> 00:27:30.560
And so there are no criteria for when you get it.

536
00:27:31.320 --> 00:27:33.810
It has to do with your,

537
00:27:33.810 --> 00:27:35.190
when their symptomatic

538
00:27:35.190 --> 00:27:37.293
or you have a high index of suspicion.

539
00:27:39.720 --> 00:27:42.480
Microvascular complications, nephropathy, retinopathy,

540
00:27:42.480 --> 00:27:45.300
neuropathy, all treated with glycemic control,

541
00:27:45.300 --> 00:27:46.503
blood pressure control.

542
00:27:48.600 --> 00:27:49.650
Retinopathy.

543
00:27:49.650 --> 00:27:51.270
Notice there's a lot, they've been asking

544
00:27:51.270 --> 00:27:52.410
a lot of questions here.

545
00:27:52.410 --> 00:27:55.380
So those tele-retinal screenings in the office

546
00:27:55.380 --> 00:27:58.830
are very good for increasing your screening.

547
00:27:58.830 --> 00:28:02.640
Patients with non-proliferative diabetic retinopathy

548
00:28:02.640 --> 00:28:05.970
should avoid exercises like power lifting,

549
00:28:05.970 --> 00:28:08.760
things that do put a lot of stress.

550
00:28:08.760 --> 00:28:13.760
And proliferative retinopathy leading to retinal detachment

551
00:28:16.094 --> 00:28:18.120
is a neovascularization problem.

552
00:28:18.120 --> 00:28:21.540
And the most common cause of sudden monocular vision loss

553
00:28:21.540 --> 00:28:23.520
is vitreous hemorrhage.

554
00:28:23.520 --> 00:28:25.110
So sorry, there's a lot of stuff there,

555
00:28:25.110 --> 00:28:27.093
but those are recent questions.

556
00:28:28.020 --> 00:28:31.380
Neuropathy's gonna be covered to some extent later.

557
00:28:31.380 --> 00:28:33.090
There's not much we can do about it

558
00:28:33.090 --> 00:28:37.320
and so symptomatic treatment and pregabalin

559
00:28:37.320 --> 00:28:40.470
and duloxetine are FDA approved.

560
00:28:40.470 --> 00:28:42.660
So they are your first line choices.

561
00:28:42.660 --> 00:28:44.610
Also amitriptyline or nortriptyline,

562
00:28:44.610 --> 00:28:46.260
but not FDA approved for that.

563
00:28:46.260 --> 00:28:48.480
And you can see the other choices there.

564
00:28:48.480 --> 00:28:50.490
Nephropathy, avoid your NSAIDs,

565
00:28:50.490 --> 00:28:54.090
manage your blood sugar and your blood pressure.

566
00:28:54.090 --> 00:28:58.410
Don't use an ACE and an ARB together, one or the other,

567
00:28:58.410 --> 00:29:02.160
and you'll get more on renal failure next,

568
00:29:02.160 --> 00:29:03.780
or in the renal talk.

569
00:29:03.780 --> 00:29:05.790
57-year-old male with diabetic foot ulcer.

570
00:29:05.790 --> 00:29:09.180
What is the best indicator of the ability to heal?

571
00:29:09.180 --> 00:29:10.920
The size of the ulcer, the patient's pulse,

572
00:29:10.920 --> 00:29:12.900
signs of infection, their blood sugar,

573
00:29:12.900 --> 00:29:14.253
or their blood pressure.

574
00:29:19.770 --> 00:29:20.670
Very good.

575
00:29:20.670 --> 00:29:23.310
The patient's pulse, most important.

576
00:29:23.310 --> 00:29:24.780
This is the diabetic foot.

577
00:29:24.780 --> 00:29:27.240
Best test for sensation is the monofilament.

578
00:29:27.240 --> 00:29:30.480
The first test is a plain film if you think they have osteo,

579
00:29:30.480 --> 00:29:32.670
but the best test is an MRI.

580
00:29:32.670 --> 00:29:36.060
The best indicator for successful healing are their pulses,

581
00:29:36.060 --> 00:29:38.160
and then you can do, if they don't have any,

582
00:29:38.160 --> 00:29:40.740
you can do an ankle brachial index.

583
00:29:40.740 --> 00:29:42.780
Please note down there what Charcot foot is,

584
00:29:42.780 --> 00:29:44.490
it sometimes appears.

585
00:29:44.490 --> 00:29:47.460
These are things that you are at increased risk for

586
00:29:47.460 --> 00:29:48.870
if you have diabetes.

587
00:29:48.870 --> 00:29:51.240
I want you to look over this slide.

588
00:29:51.240 --> 00:29:54.270
These are other complications that you see with diabetes.

589
00:29:54.270 --> 00:29:56.490
They love to ask these.

590
00:29:56.490 --> 00:29:58.560
And all they ask is, basically,

591
00:29:58.560 --> 00:30:00.270
is it associated with diabetes?

592
00:30:00.270 --> 00:30:02.430
So look over that list.

593
00:30:02.430 --> 00:30:04.710
Things like adhesive capsulitis

594
00:30:04.710 --> 00:30:06.870
and trigger finger appear a lot.

595
00:30:06.870 --> 00:30:09.390
And these are the practice recommendations.

596
00:30:09.390 --> 00:30:13.200
So thank you very much for that whirlwind tour of diabetes.

597
00:30:13.200 --> 00:30:14.132
<v Student>Thank you.</v>

598
00:30:14.132 --> 00:30:16.715
(bright music)

